  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The ATLAS Collaboration's 2012 report on the observation of a new boson consistent with the Standard Model Higgs boson stands as one of the most consequential publications in modern physics, accumulating over 10,700 citations and serving as a foundational reference across particle physics and adjacent disciplines more than a decade after its release.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Deposited on arXiv in July 2012 and subsequently published as a peer-reviewed article in Physics Letters B, this work by the ATLAS Collaboration at CERN's Large Hadron Collider reports the observation of a new particle at a mass of approximately 125 GeV, consistent with the long-sought Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model. The paper is the arXiv preprint version of a record now carrying over 10,695 citations in its journal form, with the two records together representing a cumulative scholarly footprint exceeding 10,700 citations tracked by OpenAlex \u2014 a volume that places it firmly among the most-cited physics papers of the twenty-first century. The Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded in 2013 to Peter Higgs and Fran\u00e7ois Englert in recognition of the theoretical prediction that this experimental result confirmed.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The breadth of scholarly uptake is striking both in scale and in disciplinary reach. While the core citing literature is concentrated in high-energy and particle physics \u2014 as evidenced by prominent citing venues such as SciPost Physics, SciPost Physics Community Reports, and SciPost Physics Core \u2014 the paper also draws citations from materials science (including a review of ultra-wide-bandgap semiconductor radiation detectors published in Nanotechnology) and from the philosophy of science, where it anchors discussions of model-independent experimental strategies at the LHC. This cross-disciplinary presence reflects the paper's dual role as an empirical milestone and as a methodological reference point for detector design, statistical inference, and scientific epistemology. Scite analysis records over 5,000 mention-level citations, with 136 explicitly supporting citations and only 5 contradicting citations \u2014 a profile consistent with a result that has been broadly consolidated rather than contested.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Ongoing citation activity into 2025 and 2026 confirms that the paper remains an active reference rather than a purely historical one. Recent citing works include precision calculations of top-quark pair associated Higgs production cross sections at NNLO, studies of rare few-body Higgs decays, CP-symmetry analyses employing symbolic regression, and transformer-based event classification methods for collider experiments. This pattern reflects the paper's continuing function as a definitional anchor: any new theoretical prediction or experimental measurement involving the Higgs boson must situate itself relative to the original observation. The international spread of citing institutions \u2014 spanning Germany, the United States, the United Kingdom, Italy, Switzerland, China, Sweden, and beyond \u2014 underscores that this is a genuinely global reference.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The paper is openly accessible via arXiv under green open access, ensuring that the primary record of this discovery has remained freely available to researchers worldwide regardless of institutional subscription status. Its institutional citing base, while geographically diverse, shows some concentration, with research facilities and universities \u2014 including CERN itself, the Paul Scherrer Institute, Uppsala University, and the University of Southampton, among others \u2014 appearing among the most frequent citing affiliations. The sustained and widening citation trajectory, combined with evidence of uptake in pedagogical contexts and the absence of any retractions or substantive scientific controversies, confirms this paper's status as a durable cornerstone of contemporary physics.</p>",
